**§3.1.7 — Proposed expansion:**

After the existing "Created artifacts" list, add five new subsections:

### Template source paths
Templates are bundled in the CLI package directory at `templates/`. The CLI locates its own install directory at runtime using `import.meta.url` (resolving the parent of the `src/` directory). Template source files map to destinations:

| Source (`<cliDir>/templates/`) | Destination (`.super-ralph/`) |
|---|---|
| `agents.md` | `AGENTS.md` |
| `forward.hbs` | `forward.hbs` |
| `decompose.hbs` | `decompose.hbs` |
| `reverse.hbs` | `reverse.hbs` |
| `intake-checklist.md` | `intake-checklist.md` |
| `super-ralph-config.toml` | `config.toml` (with `cli.path` patched) |

The plugin file is copied from `<cliDir>/.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js`.

### cli.path resolution
The `[cli] path` value in `config.toml` is resolved by: getting the CLI install directory via `import.meta.url` (the URL of the executing module, resolved to the parent of `src/`), then joining `src/index.ts`. The template contains `path = ""` which is replaced via regex substitution with the resolved absolute path.

### AGENTS.md content
The `.super-ralph/AGENTS.md` file is the sub-agent's primary reference for the SDLC framework. It contains:
- A heading identifying the framework
- A CLI command reference (all commands with one-line descriptions)
- Quality gate commands (e.g., `bun run typecheck`)
- File locations for config, templates, and progress log

This is deliberately concise — it's designed for AI agents to quickly understand available commands.

### Root AGENTS.md update
If root `AGENTS.md` exists and does not already contain the substring `.super-ralph/AGENTS.md`, append the line: `Also read .super-ralph/AGENTS.md for SDLC framework instructions.` If root `AGENTS.md` does not exist, create it with:
```
# Agent Instructions

Also read .super-ralph/AGENTS.md for SDLC framework instructions.
```

### intake-checklist.md content
A living document of "learned questions" read during the Reverse phase (interactive intake). It starts as a seed file with categories (Data & Storage, Security & Access, Operations, User Experience, Integration), each containing 3-5 questions the team should consider. The `LEARN-001` bead at the end of each epic appends new entries discovered during that epic. The intake skill uses judgment to select relevant questions.

